# Task: Debug ExecutionSPI Remote Mode Issues

## Problem Analysis
The java-tron works fine in:
- ✅ Traditional runtime (RuntimeImpl) 
- ✅ ExecutionSPI-aware runtime (RuntimeSpiImpl) embedded mode
- ✅ Remote storage + embedded execution
- ✅ Embedded storage + embedded execution

But fails in:
- ❌ Embedded storage + remote execution  
- ❌ Remote storage + remote execution

## Error Details
```
account [TB16q6kpSEW2WqvTJ9ua7HAoP9ugQ2HdHZ] does not exist
at org.tron.core.db.BandwidthProcessor.consume(BandwidthProcessor.java:135)
```

The error occurs during bandwidth processing when trying to validate an account that should exist.

## Investigation Plan
[X] Examine RuntimeSpiImpl implementation
[X] Check ExecutionSPI factory and remote mode setup
[X] Analyze BandwidthProcessor and account validation logic
[X] Compare embedded vs remote execution paths
[X] Identify where account state diverges in remote mode
[X] Fix the remote execution account state handling

## Fix Applied
Updated `RemoteExecutionSPI.buildExecuteTransactionRequest()` method to:
1. Extract actual transaction data from TransactionContext instead of using placeholder values
2. Properly handle different contract types (TransferContract, TransferAssetContract, CreateSmartContract, TriggerSmartContract)
3. Extract real from/to addresses, values, and contract data
4. Include proper block context information
5. Add error handling with fallback to prevent complete failure

The root cause was that bandwidth validation was failing because it was trying to validate dummy addresses instead of real transaction addresses.

## Root Cause Identified
The issue is in `RemoteExecutionSPI.buildExecuteTransactionRequest()` method. It's creating placeholder/dummy values instead of extracting actual transaction data from TransactionContext:

```java
TronTransaction.Builder txBuilder =
    TronTransaction.newBuilder()
        .setFrom(ByteString.copyFrom(new byte[20])) // TODO: Get actual from address
        .setTo(ByteString.copyFrom(new byte[20])) // TODO: Get actual to address
        // ... more placeholders
```

This means the remote execution doesn't receive proper account addresses, so when BandwidthProcessor tries to validate the account, it fails because the account doesn't exist (since it's looking for a dummy address).

## Lessons
- Remote execution mode has different account state handling than embedded mode

